No, not really. Saying that any resource that is the target of a &#39;foo&#39;  
link has certain properties is essentially expressing a type. For  
example, AtomPub specifies that resources that are listed in a  
collection are member resources. Being listed in the feed document is  
the hypermedia semantic and &#39;member&#39; is the type. AtomPub then defines  
a number of things that clients can expect to do with a member  
(essentially AtomPub defines the state transitions that are available  
after GETing a member resource.

If AtomPub did not establish the member type, it could not describe  
the expectations the client can make. (And coding the client would be  
impossible).



